Oh my goodness! If you're in San Francisco, you HAVE TO come eat here! The food is so so good! Our group of four ordered the beignet sampler - all were delicious but to our surprise we loved the savory one most. We also had omelettes, shrimp and grits and a catfish po boy that my husband said rivaled the best he's ever had in NOLA. Best time to go - between the breakfast and lunch rush (about 10:45) - but there will be a line out the door the whole time they're open.

I forced my boyfriend into doing a San Francisco adventure with me the week of Christmas. We were walking around looking for something for dinner when he popped up Brenda's on his phone. I love New Orleans and always up for trying a place that claims to be authentic. The moment we walked in, I was in love. It is a small place and very cozy but definitely had that southern vibe going on. We were seated right away but were more than willing to wait if need be. Looking at the drink and food menu, we could not contain ourselves! My only complaint does come from the drink menu. I feel like it could've had a lot more New Orleans drinks and brands. Abita is down there and makes a ton of great beer but only one was listed on the menu. Would've loved to see more southern love on the drink menu. When it comes to the food though... everything we had was amazing. Dan had to try the oyster sampler and the oysters were massive! He also had the spicy pasta, which was surprising as he is not a big pasta fan but he gobbled it right up! I had the brisket plate because I could not decide what I wanted besides everything. I knew I need to try the mac n cheese and those biscuits! That was one amazing mac n cheese. Honestly, the brisket was the weakest thing we tried. We finished our experience with the beignet sampler. Oh my goodness! Each flavor was amazing! We were so full but had to at least try a bite of each. Do not skip this place. We can't wait to try brunch there!

Then I ordered the Chicken Benedict with grit. I like the Benedict alit but I am not a fan of grit. The eggs were great. The service was really good too.

Brenda's French Soul Food has been a fixture in the San Francisco food scene for many years. With over 10,000 reviews, it's hard not to be on the forefront of every foodie's list. Housed in a modern-chic environment with lines out the door on a regular basis. This restaurant has drawn the famous Kendrick Lamar and his group to dine here ahead of their Oakland show. As the name suggested, the menu offers Southern comfort food with a French flair in a contemporary forward concept. Crispy fried chicken and grits remain staples here but, the star are their beignets- -this New Orleans special is a must when dining at Brenda's. I opted for their sampler- -Flight of Beignets which featured all four flavors and are served piping hot. By far, the crawfish beignet is my favorite. The crawfish was smothered in cheese and coated in Cajun spices inside of a fluffy pastry for a delicious taste overload. While the sweet beignets were pleasant, it wasn't as impressive as the savory one. I also ordered their chicken and andouille sausage Jambalaya served with a mixed green salad. The texture of the rice was perfect. Unfortunately, the flavors were a bit muted. It lacked the bold flavors that a Cajun dish is known for. Otherwise, it was decent. Service was a disappointment. I understand the place is busy but, as a first time customer who's trying to manuever through their menu it would have been nice for a little patience from my server. I felt rushed while putting in my order. With so many other stellar options on their menu, I am excited to return and try them out!

The gumbo was about as good as you can expect at a restaurant. It's typically a dish that's only perfect if they happen to make it the way your mama makes it, and every mama makes it different. But the hush puppies were among the best I've had. Would definitely come back when in the Bay Area.

The fried chicken was super tender and juicy and the creole hollandaise sauce was so flavorful. You can either choose a side of hash or grits and we went with the grits. The grits were super creamy! Spicy Pasta Orleans: This tasted better than I had expected! There's a lot of seafood in this pasta and the spicy pasta sauce is really creamy and but not too heavy. Beignet Flight: We couldn't decide which one to try so we got a sampler with one of each! The crawfish one is really interesting but my favorite had to be the Granny Smith Apple. I highly recommend this restaurant to anyone visiting! I'd totally come back because the service and food were both amazing. The trick is to come early to avoid the discouraging queue!

Wow!!! This place is a must try if you're in the city looking for amazingly cooked soul food! When you first come, make sure you write your name & how many people are in your party on the chalk board inside! Then you hangout in line & patiently wait for the host to call your name. I went on a Sunday morning around 10:30am, there was a line but my party only waited about 30 minutes. I ordered the fried chicken benedict with a side of hash. First of all...it was life changing! I've never had fried chicken in a form of a benedict before. I was expecting it to taste a bit too much and heavy...I was wrong! The chicken was bursting with flavor and the biscuit that the chicken was on was oddly very delicious and flavorful! My group also ordered the flight of beignets! This restaurant is the closest thing to authentic southern food, right here in the Bay Area. Can't wait to try everything on the menu.

    Brenda's French Soul Food has been a fixture in the San Francisco food scene for many years. With over 10,000 reviews, it's hard not to be on the forefront of every foodie's list.

    Housed in a modern-chic environment with lines out the door on a regular basis. This restaurant has drawn the famous Kendrick Lamar and his group to dine here ahead of their Oakland show.

    As the name suggested, the menu offers Southern comfort food with a French flair in a contemporary forward concept.

    Crispy fried chicken and grits remain staples here but, the star are their beignets- -this New Orleans special is a must when dining at Brenda's.

    I opted for their sampler- -Flight of Beignets which featured all four flavors and are served piping hot.

    Wow!!! This place is a must try if you're in the city looking for amazingly cooked soul food!

    When you first come, make sure you write your name & how many people are in your party on the chalk board inside! Then you hangout in line & patiently wait for the host to call your name. I went on a Sunday morning around 10:30am, there was a line but my party only waited about 30 minutes.

    I ordered the fried chicken benedict with a side of hash. First of all...it was life changing! I've never had fried chicken in a form of a benedict before. I was expecting it to taste a bit too much and heavy...I was wrong! The chicken was bursting with flavor and the biscuit that the chicken was on was oddly very delicious and flavorful!

    My group also ordered the flight of beignets! My favorite was the crawfish beignet, it had a kick to it and again so much flavor as well- a must try here. I tried the chocolate beignet and it was a bit too chocolate-y for my taste. If you're a chocolate fein then you'd love it. The apple beignet was really good! It contained little bits of apple, it reminded me of a warm apple pie. The plain beignet was fluffy & sweet.

    This restaurant is the closest thing to authentic southern food, right here in the Bay Area. Can't wait to try everything on the menu.

    Came here the other day after not visiting for several years and definitely tasted as good as i remembered. I came on a Tuesday around 11 and was able to sit down immediately even though the restaurant was full. I got the crawfish beignets (an always), the fried chicken benedict, and a watermelon iced tea. The crawfish beignets come with 3 pieces and they will definitely fill you up, there is enough crawfish filling inside that it goes perfectly with the beignet (not too much, not too little). The fried chicken benedict is the house special fried chicken on top of their biscuits, topped with gravy and a perfectly poached egg - comes with a side of hash or grits. The watermelon iced tea has unlimited refills and you can definitely taste the fresh watermelon juice mingling with the sweet tea (but it isn't so sweet to overwhelm). In the past i have tried and loved the shrimp & grits and fried chicken
    I highly recommend you come and try this place out. I would suggest you not come during the weekends, especially weekend brunch if you do not want to wait 1+ hours

    5/24/2019

    2 photos

    I've never been to NOLA, but my friends that I went with have and they told me that Brenda's food tasted better. And I believe them!

    I've been told the restaurant can get very busy, but we came for an early dinner midweek and were seated immediately. The staff are super kind and informative. The restaurant is definitely on the louder side, but I think the bustle and noise fit with the decor and transported you to the south, away from San Francisco.

    Our group ordered a variety of dishes, and everything was phenomenal. I ordered the Po boy sandwich with fried shrimp and oyster and the crunchiness and sweet/tangy aoli was to die for. I also got to try the chicken etouffee and spicy pasta and they fulfilled every Cajun/southern comfort desire I had.

    We of course had to end the meal with a flight of beignets which was the perfect way to end the meal. Highly recommend the beignets, as they're light and fluffy and not overpoweringly/artificially sweet.
